I have had the pleasure of working with the team at Siyan Clinical Research on their medication assisted treatment program called Project Hope.

The team at Siyan Clinical go above and beyond to understand each patient's individual psychiatric needs and provides them with an effective treatment plan in a supportive, compassionate environment.

<review>I have been seeing Teri Drew for over a year now, I have been treated with respect from the first day from both the staff and clinicians. I was initially asked by my doctor to come here for psychiatric meds as it is very tough for a medical doctor to prescribe these now that the opiod epidemic has started :( I sort of came begrudgingly, but since my health insurance was willing to foot the cost (except for a $40 copay) I decided I would go and make things easier for my doctor. I am so happy I made the decision to come in, not only have I experienced great advise and counseling, Teri has really helped me (partnered with me) to make the best decisions I can make regarding medication and life decisions, she is very knowledgeable with meds, side effects and what works with what. I can honestly state that this is the best I have felt (I am 55), my depression is non-existent, my anxieties are manageable now and my sleep cycles are returning. Teri was not forceful with her advise which helped me excel, I think she knows when you need a little push and will give that if needed, but mostly I feel this is a partnership allowing me to feel the best I can about my life! I want to state again, I have had nothing but positive attitudes from everyone I have met at Siyan and appreciate everyone from the front desk staff, to my doctor, to the doctor that filled in for her and helped me with my meds while she was away on vacation...I would definitely suggest this business to anyone that has the need! :)
I have met now with one of the other clinicians and she is terrific as well! They are doing tele visits now and that is very helpful during Covid, though their office is immaculate and they have loads of Covid protections in place.
I am also now meeting with Carrie and she is also wonderful and has many good ideas on how to curb anger and depression. I will continue to work with her on these items and many more. The staff at Siyan are all wonderful, very wonderful and helpful!<//review>< Pics>

<Text>Being the only Costa Rican Restaurant in Los Angeles area, I was really looking forward to getting some great Costa Rican food. I am sorry to say that I was disappointed. I hope that people who visit to try Costa Rican food for the first time don‚Äôt leave thinking that our food is that lousy.

I wonder if the cooks are ticas or ticos?  I say that because in Van Nuys there was a Costa Rican restaurant but the owner could not find Costa Ricans to go work for her and cook. She hired some non Costa Ricans and tried teaching them how to cook our food but it was not the same.

I also thought that the food was over priced. I think that the owner is relying on the fact the he/she has the only Costa Rican restaurant in town. If there were other Costa Rican restaurants they would have to up their game or close. Lastima!

Perhaps I am over critical as I love my country and I think that we have some of the most delicious food in Latin America. Sk I wish that there was a restaurant in the LA area that could do our food justice.<//Text>< Gmap_id>

My family went to visit one of the few Costa Rican restaurants in this country and they were treated poorly. They received horrible service, since the waitresses were watching tv and moved them from one table to another (mind you my mom is handicap). As well as once my parents were leaving, the waitresses tried to hurry them out of the handicap parking my mom was in. I do not recommend this trash customer serving restaurant. I am a proud Costa Rican and this is just not how our culture treats others. We are a happy energetic full of life culture and I'm disgusted at this location.< /text>

This is going to be a long review, so tl;dr is this: During my lease term, JRK changed the locks on my apartment and threw away my belongings.  They assumed I had vacated the apartment (a month before the end of my lease term, and the day after I paid another month's rent) without making any efforts to contact me to see if it was true. They were entirely unprofessional and unresponsive, and I finally had to retain a lawyer to help me get any kind of compensation for the queen-size bed, nightstand, desk, etc., and to get some rent back and my deposit.. As the leasing office manager told me on May 9, 2020 when I went to the office to find out why I couldn't get into my apartment, "This kind of thing happens all the time."

This happened at the Independence Green Apartments in Farmington Hills, Michigan.  A few months before the end of my lease, I moved in with my fiance to get away from Oakland County, which was quickly becoming a covid hot spot.  I returned to the apartment about once a week to get some of my things and check my mail. I continued to pay rent on time for the remaining two months of the lease.  Saturday, May 9 I arrived at my apartment to find that the locks had been changed. I called the leasing office to find out why I couldn't access my apartment. They told me my roommate and I had surrendered the unit (which we had not ‚Äî our rent had been paid, and we were both well aware of following all lease provisions regarding moving out) and my furniture had been thrown away.  The leasing office confirmed that I was current on rent and "in possession of the apartment," but would not let me into my apartment or reimburse my rent, damage deposit, or the value of any of my possessions (including the Wifi router, for which I had to pay the internet company).  The people in the leasing office were non-responsive for weeks. I finally had to get a lawyer to get them to respond.   Even then, JRK was rude, dismissive, and completely unapologetic, despite the fact that they blatantly broke not only the terms of the lease, but they broke the law (an executive order was in place regarding evictions during the Covid state of emergency).  Before retaining a lawyer, I left numerous voicemails at the JRK corporate resident relations line, since they stopped answering my phone calls. When I called with a local area code, they answered once and then stopped answering my calls again.

The manager of the leasing office told me they had emptied the apartment and changed the locks on May 1, the day after I had paid my May rent, which I did in person.  He also said they had taken pictures of what was in the apartment before it was thrown away.  I asked repeatedly to see the pictures, with no result.  Finally my lawyer had to ask, and they finally sent them, but not everything that was in the apartment was pictured.  I still don‚Äôt know - even after nearly three months -  what happened to my possessions, or to the wifi router and modem which were not included in the photographs. JRK personnel said they threw them away in the dumpster by the tennis courts.

I cannot emphasize enough what a terrible experience it was to have to work with JRK.  They purchased the complex partway through my lease term, from another company (Hayman) who had been fantastic to work with from the very beginning.  I was happy at Independence Green until JRK took over, and dealing with their illegal self-help eviction was a nightmare.  WIthout a lawyer, I don't think I would have gotten anything back at all.

My impression of JRK is that they are, at best, disorganized, unprofessional, and careless about following their own lease agreements, and, at worst, willfully dishonest. My experience at Independence Green, once pleasant and trouble-free, turned sour when JRK took over ownership. JRK offered far less than full compensation for the losses I incurred, and after the aggravation of having to deal with them, I would strongly discourage others from leasing from them.<//text>

<text>Beware before applying to any JRK properties.
Note the 5 star reviews are generated by JRK staff.

JRK property Shadow Ridge and the people who work there should be called Shady Ridge, I‚Äôve never experienced poorer customer service.
I first saw Shadow Ridge in the middle of March and liked it. The apartments were nice and our first experience was good. This ended once we paid the deposit and was approved in short order online.  We were told that the final documentation would be sent to us by the end of the week.  That date came and nothing. We waited a few days before we followed up.   After more days, we called Shadow Ridge‚Äôs phone number-the one on their website.  We were immediately sent to voicemail.  We left a message and provided a call-back number. Of course, we never received a response. By the end of the day without any return call, we tried again.  This time we got a person on the phone. I explained the issue and he was apologetic.  He said he needed to put us on hold while he looked into the problem.  We were on hold for 10-15 minutes and then unceremoniously disconnected.  Of course we called back and the call was sent directly to voicemail.  This pattern continued for over two weeks.
After chasing our tail, we sent a terse email to the customer service mailbox.  The email stated that we had been trying to finalize our lease for several weeks without success and we wanted a call to correct this problem or we would cancel our application.  Amazingly, we got a call from Shadow Ridge within ten minutes.  The woman to we spoke (Tiana) was incredibly condescending and not terribly helpful.  She explained that they were short-staffed due to covid; not surprising, but it was the first time we had received any explanation for why we had been unable to move forward with the lease.  We talked through the issues and were told that they would send the documents to us shortly.  During the call, we were, once again, placed on hold for at least 20 minutes.  We both thought that our call would be dropped before she came back on the line.  It wasn‚Äôt, making us believe that all of the other dropped calls were done purposely.  Once the lease documents were straightened out, we asked to confirm the price for the unit.  Shockingly, it was different from the price we had been quoted when we started to apply for the lease.  We expressed our objection to the change and to the way we were being treated.  Tania's response was to exclaim that we were being rude, and that if we continued to object, she would end the call.  To be clear, the difference wasn‚Äôt significant, but it was enough that when combined with the customer service problems we were already experiencing, we decided to withdraw our application and requested a refund of the application fees.  She said she could not process that refund and had to go through JRK Holding‚Äôs Tenant Relations department.
We immediately called JRK Tenant Relations and to nobody‚Äôs surprise, we got a voicemail box.  We left a message and requested a return call.  We contacted the manager, Brandy and she said that they had processed our request immediately.  We would be getting $250 less than the actual deposit per the contract. I was unhappy given that we cancelled because of their poor customer service and rudeness but it was a contract, so fine. At least they were willing to give us the $150 we are owed back.  Despite email from Brandy that she had processed, I have received no check to date.
To date, we have not received a call from the Tenant Relations department.  We have called Shadow Ridge and JRK no less than 10 times, sent emails, and left messages requesting a response.  We never received a refund from JRK or Shadow Ridge.
Shadow Ridge‚Äôs customer service is among THE WORST. I‚Äôve had a had a root canal better than this experience.</text><user_id>100556235662977613705<//user_id><pictures>None< /pictures><Response>None</Response><Time>1593875875935<//Time>< name>

< review>
Renters beware:

After a year and a half, and I should have gotten out when my lease ended in the first apartment. The first unit move in experience was horrible. We moved into a unit that didn't have a deadbolt lock on the door, holes in the walls from things that the previous resident had hung, and a huge hole in the ceiling from a water leak, filthy carpets which also included damage from pets and needed stretched and paint was spilled on the carpet, master bath tub needed resurfaced from horrid stains from the AC backup drain which was rusted and left rust all over the tile, poop was backed up in the master bathroom toilet, food stains all over the kitchen walls and ceiling, the exhaust fan didn't work, the plastic piece at the top of the microwave was broken, the kitchen sink leaked, our dryer was not hooked up correctly, we didn't have a mailbox key for two months, no garage keys, and had to replace our storage room deadbolt ourselves because they had no keys for that as well. Over time there was a rodent problem and I found dead mice in the storage room. I patched all the holes myself and out of my own pocket, constantly had to clean the rust drip stains from the backup AC pipe that seemed to always be leaking, and when our dryer was fixed, there was a huge spark that flew from the dryer to the carpet and caused permanent damage to the carpet. We also were woken up at 2am one morning because our smoke detectors had malfunctioned, and it turned out the fire department said that the smoke detectors should have been replaced a long time ago due to the age of them.

At the end of the lease, I decided to move into a one bedroom apartment, which required a transfer. My move in for the second apartment was better than my first one but still had issues. The day of my move in was scheduled on a Saturday, in which I was informed a few days prior that they did not do move ins on a Saturday. I then had to change all moving arrangements last minute to Friday, which cost me an extra day's rent with no notice. The day of my move in, I could not move in as the carpets were being cleaned after I received my keys. I had to change my moving arrangements back to Saturday because of this. Once I was able to move in, there were stains in the carpet, after being cleaned, light bulbs were out, which I replaced myself, and the garage remote did not work. I did not have a garage for a week, and when I finally received my garage, there was a hole in the wall, into the garage next to mine, and both light bulbs inside were burnt out. I have requested they fix these issues multiple times since September, and it is now January and they keep changing my status of my maintenance request to "fixed". After transferring, I had received notice that I owed money towards the first apartment because I did not get the carpets cleaned. Jana had told me she would take it off, since the carpets were not cleaned prior to my original move in, nor were they stretched at all after my multiple attempts to request maintenance to fix this issue. Because the issue was never fixed during my time in this apartment she had agreed to reverse this and call the company they use for collections. After receiving a second collections notice, I went back and spoke with Victoria who had pulled Jana aside and asked her about it, in which I was told would be taken care of. The third time I went in a spoke with Jordan, who pulled up my transactions and said it looked like it was reversed on the complex's end but would follow up with Jana about the collections end. He took a copy of the letter and wrote my info down. Then I received notice weeks later that it finally affected my credit score. At this point, Jana, Jordan, and Victoria no longer work for JRK. I spoke with the new manager, Brandy, and explained my situation and what has been going on. Brandy informed me that what I thought was the "reversal" was actually a "write off" to the collections agency. She gave me the number to JRK's resident hotline.

JRK will not return my calls.</review>

<user_name>John Bartell< /user_name><text>Interesting corporate policies?

About a month ago one of my kids applied (along with a roommate) to this company for an apartment. First they hit them with a $55 per person application fee (cost for credit bureau full background checks are typically about $30 - so there is some extra money for their "time"), but then came the other fees! A $205 dollar "administrative" fee (what is that for?), Utility transfer fee $25 (they don't own the utility - the utility company transfers the account - but they still have a charge), Fitness key fee $35 (keys cost about $2) ALL THESE FEES ARE NON-REFUNDABLE. By the time they were through, together they were out about $350, only to be told 2 days before move in day that they were not approved. Up to almost the last moment The office persons repeatedly said  "we can't wait for you to move in", "we're really excited to have you here".

This business is preying on the tight rental market and creating a revenue stream from applications instead of providing housing. Charging outrageous, unjustifiable fees to persons that can least afford it. Think of how this affects the people who apply. very quickly a person would spend hundreds of dollars for bogus fees then they can't afford their first months rent.

<Name>Brittney W<//Name><Time>1546890248367<//Time><rate>1< /rate>< review>
The specific issues that I had with JRK were with properties in Colorado. To start, I work in property management, both residential and commercial. I have never experience such incredible amounts of disrespect, incompetence, and flat our negligence, and this was just during the application process. I would hate to have to experience what the residents living at these communities are going through.

The leasing agent was dressed so unprofessionally, jeans and a tank top, and wouldn't even acknowledge people walking through the door. She continued to ask for copies of SSN's and drivers licenses multiple times, even though all the information was on the application. She mentioned that the applications were approved but she needed SSN and Driver license information again. She wanted copies emailed to her...Why would you need that information again if the application already came back approved? It was starting to feel very off. After reading several other reviews that mentioned scamming, things started to click. She tried to get the application/holding fees twice from us, stating that payment never went through even through the payment came out of the bank and we had bank statements to prove it. She tried to charge double the security deposit because she only screened one applicant at first, and wouldn't screen the other for days.

I was getting frustrated and called their corporate headquarters. No one answered, and I left a message explaining the situation and asked for a call back. I have yet to received a call back... Seems like they wanted to take the money and give us the run around, and if that was not the case, JRK you have a lot to work on.

We caught the agent purposefully ignoring our phone calls. She even hung up on us. The community was a perfect fit, however with the extreme lack of customer service we chose to look elsewhere for a home. Colorado has a very LARGE market of apartments, do not sacrifice customer service for beauty, trust me you can have both.

This was an identical experience I had with a JRK Property a year ago. I thought it was just that one location, but it sounds like this is a company standard.

Please do your research before moving into a JRK Community.< /review>

<Rating>1< /Rating>< Review>
I had the complete circus-like experience of living in TerraMar in Santa Rosa Beach, Florida, for over a year, before I became the Leasing Assistant in the front office. What an eye opening experience it was... to say the least.  During my employment Shelly Marlin, was the Property Manager and then was promoted to Regional Manager. I observed more deceptive business practices and law breaking acts while employed there than I could have ever imagined. Applications were altered, lies were told to anyone and everyone who walked in to the office, company polices were not only NOT followed...they were completely ignored and broken, cash was taken from residents, and kept in Shelly's office,  this cash was for payments and this specific resident, Lee Fox... well...I continually saw him bring in his cash...also had the code to enter her office. The multiple car keying episodes that went on for months was a hush-hush topic, and we were not to tell any truth on what we knew, as employees. Like I said...a complete circus. The amount of fraud that I witnessed, was appalling.  As both a resident, and an employee there, I was told I would receive an employee discount, after I had worked 90 days. Well... imagine my surprise, when 30 days after my 90 days...still waiting on word for my discount...I was told that Christopher Murray, who is located in California and was Shelly's boss, had decided to go up on my rent, and then I could get an employee discount. Hmmm... It was so like them to NOT keep their word. What a great feeling of being valued,  I worked my tail off...most days without any break or lunch.  I did not ever receive any pay or compensation for hours each week that I had worked over. Funny how Shelly made sure that I was told that I would NOT be considered for re-hire, since I gave 13 days notice not 14. When no discount was going to be given to me... I resigned, with 13 days notice... I was never ever given a new lease, paid my rent on time every month, the increase amount was sent to me in a text, nothing in writing. On June 10th 2017, I received an eviction notice on my door from Brandi Polvado, who was the Property Manager at that time. I hired an attorney. No one would call my attorney back, no one would explain why I was being evicted, without a lease. I was also current on my rent each month.  They were all such fools from day one. I moved out August 2, 2017, received a collection notice, a few weeks later...I never got a bill, never received my deposit. Thankfully...JRK has a reputation here as does TerraMar.  Small towns listen to what people are saying.  Thank goodness there is another apartment that is new in the area.  Beware...use caution...and take time to read what other people have taken the time to share.  JRK and TerraMar are very similar to a $3 bill.  PHONY!!!<//Review>

< Text>
The specific issues that I had with JRK were with properties in Colorado. To start, I work in property management, both residential and commercial. I have never experience such incredible amounts of disrespect, incompetence, and flat our negligence, and this was just during the application process. I would hate to have to experience what the residents living at these communities are going through.

The leasing agent was dressed so unprofessionally, jeans and a tank top, and wouldn't even acknowledge people walking through the door. She continued to ask for copies of SSN's and drivers licenses multiple times, even though all the information was on the application. She mentioned that the applications were approved but she needed SSN and Driver license information again. She wanted copies emailed to her...Why would you need that information again if the application already came back approved? It was starting to feel very off. After reading several other reviews that mentioned scamming, things started to click. She tried to get the application/holding fees twice from us, stating that payment never went through even through the payment came out of the bank and we had bank statements to prove it. She tried to charge double the security deposit because she only screened one applicant at first, and wouldn't screen the other for days.

I was getting frustrated and called their corporate headquarters. No one answered, and I left a message explaining the situation and asked for a call back. I have yet to received a call back... Seems like they wanted to take the money and give us the run around, and if that was not the case, JRK you have a lot to work on.

We caught the agent purposefully ignoring our phone calls. She even hung up on us. The community was a perfect fit, however with the extreme lack of customer service we chose to look elsewhere for a home. Colorado has a very LARGE market of apartments, do not sacrifice customer service for beauty, trust me you can have both.

This was an identical experience I had with a JRK Property a year ago. I thought it was just that one location, but it sounds like this is a company standard.

Please do your research before moving into a JRK Community.</Text>

< review>
Since JRK bought the Residences at Stevens Pond in Saugus, MA in the summer of 2014, the quality of the property and quality of life has dramatically diminished each year to the point where it has become unbearable and overly expensive to continue to reside here.
Some examples:
Longtime residents, who get hit with the exorbitant annual rent hikes, are never provided any regular preventative maintenance in their units nor is normal wear and tear of the residence ever addressed.
The grounds are filthy and disgusting. Taking a walk throughout the property, here are some of the things you will encounter on the grounds: trash/litter everywhere including spilling out of the compactors, dog feces, living/dead rats, cigarette butts, hypodermic needles, used condoms, dirty baby diapers, screws and nails on the road and in parking spots, empty beer cans/bottles, empty wine and nip bottles, broken glass, discarded clothing.  Residents keep prohibited dog breeds in their apartments, commercial vehicles take up all the parking spots, and decks/driveways are cluttered with unsightly furniture, boxes, etc. Residents freely smoke in their units even though it is prohibited. These conditions/issues are not addressed by management.
There is no landscaping. Lawns and shrubbery throughout the complex desperately need replacing. Curbs/sidewalks, outdoor lighting are broken/cracked and never fixed/replaced.
The snow removal has been deplorable. Even after the "clean up" during which your newly shoveled car gets plowed back in until they come back to dig it out hours/day later, parking and getting around the property is always very difficult. Property managers/staff don't last long, but most of them have been ineffective anyway. While they were here most of them did little to nothing to alleviate concerns. In fact, they were usually quite rude. Apparently JRK does not provide customer service training. Sarcasm, nastiness and turning the issues/blame back on the residents are standard practice. Calling corporate is just as useless. The tenant line is always "full" and voice messages, emails never returned. The "IKEA" makeover of the offices, clubhouse and pool that took way longer than scheduled was completely unwarranted. A good cleaning, sprucing up would have been adequate.  Besides the new amenities are not properly maintained and the gym, game room, clubhouse bathrooms, pool area are dirty and disgusting to the point where they are sometimes unusable. At night the basketball court/gym is taken over by who even knows (I hear they are not even residents). Security is much needed here but is nonexistent.
To sum up, the website is false advertising and this is a horrible, horrible place to live!< /review>

< Review>
JRK Property Holdings seems to be okay with its properties being run without any respect to the law or human decency. They owe me $533 and I have legitimate security concerns with regards to one of their property managers, and their response is to ignore the issue and send my calls to a voicemail box. Below is my full story-

We were tenants at Shadow Ridge at Southlands in Aurora, CO from June of 2016 to June of 2018. We paid rent and utilities in full and on time every month, and left the apartment in cleaner and nicer condition than we received it. We have receipt of surrendering the premise on 28 May 2018. We received neither our security deposit nor an itemized bill within 60 days of surrender, nor within 60 days of the end of the lease. This is a violation of Colorado Revised Statute 38-12-103 (2). We mailed our certified  7 day demand letter and served proper notice of our small claims case to the property management at Shadow Ridge. After failing to appear in court, a default judgement was entered against their property Shadow Ridge. We are now owed $533 for the illegal retention of our security deposit. I also have concerns about their property manager Tamara Huber. Despite multiple contacts (and proof of contact) with her about this issue, she denied any knowledge of it and became  verbally abusive to her staff and myself. Her behavior was absolutely reprehensible and unprofessional- I am shocked no one called the police on her for screaming the way she did in her back office. I have exchanged contact information with another tenant who witnessed Ms. Huber's meltdown for corroboration. Regardless of any issues I may have with her for illegally keeping our deposit, no employee (no human being for that matter) should be treated the way she was treating others today (screaming in her back office at employees for ~30 minutes). I feel very unsafe knowing that such a seemingly unstable person has access to our information and forwarding address.

To see sort of treatment and customer service that JRK Property Holdings is condoneing and finds acceptable, search "Shadow Ridge" on Youtube.</Review>

I've been in the workforce for over 40 years,  and I've worked for a variety of companies and held jobs for about 7 years on average.   JRK is at the bottom of my list of companies that I think someone should work for.   I never experienced micromanagement like I did at JRK.  I got the impression that they don't trust any of there employees.  My manager actually said to me,  very early on in my employment,  "the company we work for has trust issues.".   That is actually a gross understatement in my humble opinion.   I would never recommend that anyone work for this company,  or live in there properties.  I saw nothing that told me this company has any ability to respect it's employees or residents.   I felt complicit in what I felt was the unfair treatment of residents while I worked for this company.  I could not,  in good conscious,  continue to remain in their employ.  It seemed as though all that mattered was to squeeze as much profit as possible without any non financial criteria ever considered.  It's difficult to state these opinions strongly enough. <userid>112661145058718191601< /userid><name>Richie Newland< /name><Date>1401845663575</Date><Rate>1</Rate><Review>Caution: DO NOT RENT with JRK!!!!
I was a resident of their apartment buildings at Centreport Lake Apartments, Fort Worth, TX during my job assignment in the area for approximately 17/18 months. It all seemed well as it looks kept up. Let me just say, that's simply window dressing. The staff on site is less than professional. They look the part, and even talk it when you are face to face. However, on numerous occasions we would call to have our bathtub drain unplugged (yeah, there was was down the drain). Maintenance wouldn't show up for the remainder of that day or the next. We would have to physically walk to the office to request this because they don't write anything down. We have a dog, and as such we are very much on top of our responsibilities to clean up after him. We walk around with baggies all the time just in case. However, we were in the minority. There is dog poop all over the common grounds. We complained about this as well, and only flyers went went out reminding pet owners to clean up after themselves. The poop situation did not get any better in the entire time we lived there. Another constant is that the security gates will be broken. They tout a gated community for your safety, however at least one of the gates was open at all times at least once every other week. They don't get fixed immediately either. It's nothing to find the gates open for 4-5 days at a time before they're working for about a week before being broken again. These, in our minds, were minor inconveniences. After all, we were only there for a short time before returning home.
The big kicker though, is after you move out, and the reason that I'm writing a review. We asked for a walk-thru the day prior to moving out. They didn't show up. Being that we were driving from Texas to Michigan, we left the next day well before the offices opened. During this last week we were in constant contact with the office. Paid our break-lease fees, rent, overages for our utilities so we wouldn't have to worry about it. Fast forward one month.... a call from a collection agency. Keep in mind, we have heard nothing from Centreport Lake Apartments or JRK Asset Management. Apparently, they don't grant you a courtesy of letting you know you owe them money. We owe them above $600, but less than $700. For what? They had to replace the carpet, the same carpet that we noted was in bad shape when we moved in. However, they claim the dog peed on it all over even though either my wife or I was home with the dog 24/7. I can assure you it wasn't from our dog. Regardless, the carpet needed replacing anyway and they conveniently could not find our initial checklist noting the damage to the carpet prior to moving in. We did not hang pictures or damage walls, there was nothing to suggest that we damaged it. What this complex will do, is wait until you move out and if your apartment needs some renovations, you are footing the bill.
I would caution anyone to rent from such shady businesses. Unfortunately I am seeing this first-hand now. You may be lucky and rent an apartment that needs no work and get out with minimal charges. I just wanted to be a cautionary tale for anybody else out there who might think they look like nice apartments, there's a whole slew of underlying problems with this place. They received 1 star from me (Hated It), mostly because I could not give them 0 stars!</Review>< pics>

< text>
I needed a storage unit while I was moving houses and Angelica was exceptionally helpful through the process of keeping the unit reserved while I waited for escrow.

The former manager, John, and the current manager, Patricia, keep the facilities very clean and are able to provide quality service over the phone or when I walk in (and I walk in a lot).

The security there is excellent, the exteriors well lit with complete coverage of the driveway, and the buildings climate control makes this location incredible. Nothing like the typical storage places.

I would absolutely recommend this location and it's staff to everyone I know, especially if you enjoy solid concrete walls and a controlled indoor environment instead of the typical humid, musty plywood partition storage facilities.< /text>

<user>100116065148623257338<//user><pictures>None< /pictures><review>I looked at one other newer storage facility in the midtown area of Sacramento, and this place was hands down above and beyond.  The person that helped us, Patricia, was so helpful, and made sure to let us know how to get a $25 discount by reserving the unit online, even though we were there in person.  The grounds are so clean, and the unit was impeccably clean as well.  All units are behind the drive through gate, which I love, and each unit has its own individual gate code, which also unlocks the security system for your individual unit!  Unlike the other place I looked at, the box where you enter your code can be accessed without leaving your car, allowing you to just pull right up and enter the code and drive through.  There are multiple entrances to the inside areas, making it convenient to park closer to your unit if its not near the first door.  Plenty of carts right inside the door as well.  They also are converting all of their units to cylinder locks, which means your unit is extra secure.  Haven't put anything in my unit yet, but I am extremely satisfied with my experience, highly recommend!</review>< rate>

< review>
Buyers beware. They offer great discounts to reel you in and then spring lots of hidden costs. In my case i booked a 5x10 unit for $47/month for 1st three months. The lady (amber) at the call center told me there was "small" $10 admin fee added which included the price of lock.
So I drive from Grass Valley hiring a U haul truck on which i pay .89 cents/mile. Load everything into it and arrive at their facility at around 1 PM. I am told that I have to pay a $20 insurance and i cannot opt out of it further the admin fee is now $25 and not $10.
At this point of time i cannot take the U haul back as the that costs me $100 for the day with mileage. So I have no other option but to cough up 47+20+25=$92.
As a consolation the manager tells me there many other people complaining about the call center and we are not the first people like that.
The only good part of this experience was the manager came and gave me hand with lifting a chest of drawers.</review>

<review>This is an excellent storage facility, although pricey. Most of the units are climate controlled (i.e., air conditioning and heating for the whole building, not individually controlled), and therefore not prone to dust build-up or damage from temperature extremes. The staff is friendly, and they offer free use of their truck to move-in (or move-out if you didn't use it on move-in). They also provide flat-bed dollies to help move your stuff in and out of the units. Elevators make upper-floor access very easy. Each unit is individually alarmed, and they have good camera coverage over the whole site. My only complaint is that the whole time I was there (about 10 years), they increased the rental rate every few years. Sure, the rates in the whole area went up, too, but just be aware that the rate you start out at will probably go up in a year or two. Otherwise, it was a great place to store our stuff.<//review><Pics>None<//Pics><Rate>5< /Rate><gmapID>0x809adac302af3a89:0x2c69fccf9970592f<//gmapID><user_name>Will Murray (Willscrlt)< /user_name>< response>

<text>This McDonalds has recently finished renovating.   The interior has greatly improved, and looks much cleaner and modern.

The food is your standard McDonald's, with variances based on who's cooking.  They will often meet your special requests, but it's hit or miss sometimes.   They've gotten small things wrong (ie: mayonnaise on a no mayonnaise order).  The manager, Oscar, will do whatever is needed to fix it and have you leave happy.

The WiFi is bad, so don't expect to stream movies or TV shows while connected inside. The bathroom could use work as well.< /text><Pics>None< /Pics><resp>None</resp><Gmap_id>0x80c2cec3afd11c51:0x71516d3ea68c41d1<//Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>
